Description: Complete small seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation. The rear shows three sides (trapezoidal in section) with impressions that are difficult to define. One side shows compartments that might originate from a basket-like object, a second side is shaped slightly convex and the third side shows an impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25 cm. The front side is convex and is covered in finger impressions. It shows most parts of a scarab-like seal impression, showing a lying crocodile facing to the left, underneath a standing bull, facing to the left as well.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
